docs.abstract: While House Democratic leaders agonize, black voters want President Trump impeached, and their ardor on the subject is driving their representatives.
docs.snippet: While House Democratic leaders agonize, black voters want President Trump impeached, and their ardor on the subject is driving their representatives.
docs.lead_paragraph: PHILADELPHIA — Moments after the special counsel, Robert S. Mueller III, wrapped up his appearance at the Justice Department on Wednesday, Representative Dwight Evans stepped out of his district office in a black working-class neighborhood here to visit with local business owners. They had one question on their minds: Why is President Trump still in office?

headline.main: Black Voters Challenge House Members: Why Is Trump Still in Office?

docs.abstract: The threat to impose tariffs on Mexico was a case study in President Trump’s approach to some of the most daunting issues confronting him and the nation.
docs.snippet: The threat to impose tariffs on Mexico was a case study in President Trump’s approach to some of the most daunting issues confronting him and the nation.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — For nine days, he had his finger on the trigger and threatened to pull. For nine days, he put two countries, entire multinational industries, vast swaths of consumers and workers and even his own advisers and Republican allies on edge, unsure what would happen with billions of dollars at stake.

headline.main: A Drama of Trump’s Own Making Ends With a Familiar Hero
headline.print_headline: Self-Made Crisis and a Predictable Hero

docs.abstract: The Trump administration will be ending a major university contract involving fetal tissue research and will soon stop such work at the National Institutes of Health.
docs.snippet: The Trump administration will be ending a major university contract involving fetal tissue research and will soon stop such work at the National Institutes of Health.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The Trump administration announced Wednesday that the federal government would sharply curtail federal spending on medical research that uses tissue from aborted fetuses, mainly by ending fetal-tissue research within the National Institutes of Health.

headline.main: Trump Administration Sharply Curtails Fetal Tissue Medical Research
headline.print_headline: Curbs Ordered On Studies’ Use Of Fetal Tissue

docs.abstract: President Trump, at two events on Tuesday in London, made inaccurate claims about trade, protests against him, Brexit and his approval rating.
docs.snippet: President Trump, at two events on Tuesday in London, made inaccurate claims about trade, protests against him, Brexit and his approval rating.
docs.lead_paragraph: When it comes to international trade, the United States’ top partners so far this year are Mexico, Canada and China, with total trade amounting to $150.6 billion, $146.6 billion and $132 billion. Britain ranked seventh at $33.1 billion. Last year, top trading partners were China ($659.8 billion), Canada ($617.2 billion) and Mexico ($611.5 billion), and Britain placed seventh ($127 billion).

headline.main: Fact-Checking Trump’s London Visit: Trade, Protests, Brexit
headline.print_headline: Presidential Trail Of Inaccurate Claims Finds Way to Britain

docs.abstract: In a contentious meeting at the Capitol, Senate Republicans told senior White House officials that they are prepared to resist tariffs on Mexico if President Trump pushes forward.
docs.snippet: In a contentious meeting at the Capitol, Senate Republicans told senior White House officials that they are prepared to resist tariffs on Mexico if President Trump pushes forward.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Republican senators sent the White House a sharp message on Tuesday, warning that they were almost uniformly opposed to President Trump’s plans to impose tariffs on Mexican imports, just hours after the president said lawmakers would be “foolish” to try to stop him.

headline.main: Senate Republicans Warn White House Against Mexico Tariffs
headline.print_headline: Pressured by President, Republicans Push Back On Mexico Tariff Threat

docs.abstract: If the president follows through on issuing a plan, it could help shape a presidential race that Democrats would like to focus largely on health care.

docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — As President Trump prepares to kick off his bid for a second term this week, he is anxiously searching for a way to counter Democrats on health care, one of their central issues, even though many of his wary Republican allies would prefer he let it go for now.

headline.main: Trump Wants to Neutralize Democrats on Health Care. Republicans Say Let It Go.
